{"title_page": "Joseph and Luka Banda", "text_new": "{{notability|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name = Joseph and Luka Banda\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1997|01|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lusaka]], [[Zambia]]\n| known_for = [[Conjoined twins]]<br>(1997\uff0d2001)\n}}\n'''Joseph Banda''' and '''Luka Banda''' (born 23 January 1997)<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924181608/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-6375253.html Zambia: Zambian Siamese Twins Return Home] Chibi Kubantu, Inter Press Service English News Wire 1998-04-09 (subscription required)</ref> are twin brothers who used to be conjoined. They were born joined at the back of the skull and faced in opposite directions. In 1997, [[Ben Carson]] led a team of 50 Zambian and South African specialists to separate the 11-month-old twins in a 28-hour operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2002/HEALTH/08/10/separated.zambian.twins/ |title=African separated twins offer hope for 'little Marias' |publisher=CNN.com |date=2002-08-10 |accessdate=2015-10-22}}</ref> They did not share any organs, but shared intricate blood vessels that flowed into each other's brains. In 2001, the twins were fitted with artificial skulls to permanently close their heads, and are neurologically normal. In an interview, Carson stated about the operation:\n:\"In the end, the Bandas became the first Type 2 [[craniopagus twins]] (joined at the head and facing in opposite directions) ever separated with both surviving and both being neurologically normal.\"''<ref>{{cite news|last=Dreifus |first=Claudia |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E1D81E38F937A35752C0A9669C8B63 |title=A CONVERSATION WITH - BENJAMIN S. CARSON - A Pioneer at a Frontier - The Brain of a Child |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2000-01-04 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThey are residing in an area of Lusaka called Chilenje South.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.daily-mail.co.zm/luka-joseph-at-21/|title=Luka, Joseph at 21 \u2013 Zambia Daily Mail|website=www.daily-mail.co.zm|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1268638.stm BBC article - Joined at the head: medical briefing] Monday, 9 April 2001 \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060304101238/http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/press/1998/JANUARY/980115.HTM Hopkins Medicine article] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051128143242/http://www.udel.edu/PR/UpDate/00/33/carson.html \"Commencement 2000 - Ben Carson discussion of the operation]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banda, Joseph and Luka}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conjoined twins]]\n[[Category:People from Lusaka]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Zambia]]\n\n\n{{Zambia-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name = Joseph and Luka Banda\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1997|01|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lusaka]], [[Zambia]]\n| known_for = [[Conjoined twins]]<br>(1997\uff0d2001)\n}}\n'''Joseph Banda''' and '''Luka Banda''' (born 23 January 1997)<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924181608/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-6375253.html Zambia: Zambian Siamese Twins Return Home] Chibi Kubantu, Inter Press Service English News Wire 1998-04-09 (subscription required)</ref> are twin brothers who used to be conjoined. They were born joined at the back of the skull and faced in opposite directions. In 1997, [[Ben Carson]] led a team of 50 Zambian and South African specialists to separate the 11-month-old twins in a 28-hour operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2002/HEALTH/08/10/separated.zambian.twins/ |title=African separated twins offer hope for 'little Marias' |publisher=CNN.com |date=2002-08-10 |accessdate=2015-10-22}}</ref> They did not share any organs, but shared intricate blood vessels that flowed into each other's brains. In 2001, the twins were fitted with artificial skulls to permanently close their heads, and are neurologically normal. In an interview, Carson stated about the operation:\n:\"In the end, the Bandas became the first Type 2 [[craniopagus twins]] (joined at the head and facing in opposite directions) ever separated with both surviving and both being neurologically normal.\"''<ref>{{cite news|last=Dreifus |first=Claudia |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E1D81E38F937A35752C0A9669C8B63 |title=A CONVERSATION WITH - BENJAMIN S. CARSON - A Pioneer at a Frontier - The Brain of a Child |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2000-01-04 |accessdate=2015-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThey are residing in an area of Lusaka called Chilenje South.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1268638.stm BBC article - Joined at the head: medical briefing] Monday, 9 April 2001 \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060304101238/http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/press/1998/JANUARY/980115.HTM Hopkins Medicine article] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051128143242/http://www.udel.edu/PR/UpDate/00/33/carson.html \"Commencement 2000 - Ben Carson discussion of the operation]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banda, Joseph and Luka}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conjoined twins]]\n[[Category:People from Lusaka]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Zambia]]\n\n\n{{Zambia-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bruston", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added citation 4", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_and_Luka_Banda"}
{"title_page": "Misplaced Ideals", "text_new": "{{short description|1978 album by Sad Caf\u00e9}}\n{{use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Misplaced Ideals\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Sad Caf\u00e9]]\n| cover        = Sad Caf\u00e9 Misplaced Ideals UK original.jpg\n| caption      = Original vinyl cover\n| released     = April 1978\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{hlist|[[Sawmills Studios]], Cornwall|[[Air Studios]], London}}\n| genre        = [[Pop rock]]\n| length       = 42:06\n| label        = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer     = [[John Punter]]\n| prev_title   = [[Fanx Ta-ra|Fanx Ta-Ra]]\n| prev_year    = 1977\n| next_title   = [[Misplaced Ideals#North American album|Misplaced Ideals]]\n| next_year    = 1978\n| misc         = {{Extra album cover\n | type    = album \n | header  = Alternative cover\n | cover   = Sad Caf\u00e9 Misplaced Ideals UK reissue.jpg\n | caption = Reissue vinyl cover\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Misplaced Ideals''''' is the second studio album by English rock band [[Sad Caf\u00e9]], released in April 1978<ref>{{Cite magazine|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|first=|date=22 April 1978|editor-last=|editor-first=|title=Record Mirror|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Record-Mirror/70s/78/1978-04-22.pdf|magazine=|publisher=|volume=|issue=|page=5|pages=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> by [[RCA Records]]. Despite no singles being released from the album and its lack of commercial success, it peaked at number 50 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldofgenesis.com/Biography-PaulYoung.htm|title=World of Genesis - Paul Young - A Brief History 1947-2000|website=www.worldofgenesis.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/misplaced-ideals/|title=misplaced ideals {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The album wasn't released in US or Canada, where instead it was decided that a compilation album, also titled ''[[Misplaced Ideals#North American album|Misplaced Ideals]]'', of the band's first two albums be released. \n\nThe album cover also fell under some scrutiny and RCA decided to take action and substitute it for a picture of family of sunbathers walking on a beach when it was reissued in Europe. The North American album also has a different cover<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Track Listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Restless\n| writer5 = Wilson\n| length1 = 4:38\n| title2 = Here Come the Clowns\n| writer2 = Young\n| length2 = 4:00\n| title3 = Run Home Girl\n| writer3 = Young, Wilson\n| length3 = 6:04\n| title4 = Let Love Speak for Itself\n| writer4 = Young, Stimpson, Wilson\n| length4 = 6:08\n| title5 = No Place to Go\n| writer1 = John Stimpson, [[Paul Young (singer, born 1947)|Paul Young]], Ian Wilson, Ashley Mulford\n| title6 = Mario\n| length5 = 4:51\n| writer6 = Young, [[Vic Emerson]], Stimpson\n| length6 = 3:45\n| title7 = Relax\n| writer7 = Young\n| length7 = 3:17\n| title8 = Feel Like Dying\n| writer8 = Young\n| length8 = 4:09\n| title9 = On With the Show\n| writer9 = Young, Wilson, Emerson, Mulford, Stimpson\n| length9 = 5:14\n| total_length = 42:06\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n'''Sad Caf\u00e9'''\n\n* [[Paul Young (singer, born 1947)|Paul Young]] \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n* Ashley Mulford \u2013 [[lead guitar]]\n* [[Vic Emerson]] \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n* John Stimpson \u2013 [[bass guitar]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n* Ian Wilson \u2013 [[electric guitar]], [[acoustic guitar]], backing vocals, percussion\n* Tony Cresswell \u2013 [[Drum|drums]]\n\n'''Additional personnel'''\n\n* Lenny Sachs \u2013 [[saxophone]]\n* [[John Punter]] \u2013 additional percussion\n* [[Doreen Chanter]], [[Irene Chanter]], Liza Strike \u2013 additional vocals on \"Feel Like Dying\"\n* Nigel Walker, Jon Walls \u2013 assistant engineers\n* Vic Emerson \u2013 strings arrangement and synthesisation\n* Iain Scott \u2013 photography of live band\n* [[Hipgnosis]] \u2013 sleeve design and photography\n\n== North American album ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Misplaced Ideals\n| type         = compilation\n| artist       = [[Sad Caf\u00e9]]\n| cover        = Sad Caf\u00e9 Misplaced Ideals US.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = November 1978\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Pop rock]]\n| length       = 44:20\n| label        = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| producer     = [[John Punter]]\n| next_title   = Fa\u00e7ades\n| next_year    = 1979\n}}\n\n{{album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/misplaced-ideals-mw0000793579|title=''Misplaced Ideals'' \u2013 Sad Caf\u00e9 <nowiki>| Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |</nowiki> AllMusic |last=Boldman|first=Gina|website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[Robert Christgau]]\n| rev3score = C-<ref>{{cite web|last1=Christgau|first1=Robert|title=Sad Caf\u00e9|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Sad+Cafe|website=robertchristgau.com|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThis album was only released in the US and Canada and is a compilation of songs from Sad Caf\u00e9's first two albums, ''[[Fanx Ta-ra]]'' and ''Misplaced Ideals'', neither of which were released there.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was released in November 1978 by [[A&M Records]]. \"Run Home Girl\" and \"Feel Like Dying\" were released as singles, with the former reaching number 71 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in 1979.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/sad-cafe|title=Sad Caf\u00e9|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The album also charted at number 94 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \"Run Home Girl\" is also a shorter, edited version of the original UK release.\n\nThe album was reissued on CD in 2008 by [[Renaissance Records]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.renaissancerecordsus.com/sadcafe.html|title=Sad Cafe|website=www.renaissancerecordsus.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> and the 2011 album download included 4 bonus tracks, which were the four songs from the original UK release of the album not included on this compilation.<ref>{{Citation|title=Sad Caf\u00e9: Misplaced Ideals - Music Streaming - Listen on Deezer|url=https://www.deezer.com/en/album/910857|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Track Listing ===\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Restless\n| writer1 = John Stimpson, [[Paul Young (singer, born 1947)|Paul Young]], Ian Wilson, Ashley Mulford\n| length1 = 4:36\n| title2 = Here Come the Clowns\n| writer2 = Young\n| length2 = 4:00\n| title3 = Run Home Girl\n| writer3 = Young, Wilson\n| length3 = 4:57\n| title4 = Black Rose\n| writer4 = Young, Stimpson\n| length4 = 4:36\n| title5 = I Believe Love (Will Survive)\n| writer5 = Young\n| length5 = 4:29\n| title6 = Babylon\n| writer6 = Young\n| length6 = 3:40\n| title7 = Shellshock\n| writer7 = Sad Caf\u00e9\n| length7 = 3:12\n| title8 = Hungry Eyes\n| writer8 = Young, [[Vic Emerson]]\n| length8 = 5:26\n| title9 = Feel Like Dying\n| writer9 = Young\n| length9 = 4:09\n| title10 = On With the Show\n| writer10 = Young, Wilson, Emerson, Mulford, Stimpson\n| length10 = 5:15\n| total_length = 44:20\n}}\n\n2011 download bonus tracks:\n{{Track listing\n| title11 = Let Love Speak for Itself\n| writer11 = Young, Stimpson, Wilson\n| length11 = 6:09\n| title12 = Mario\n| writer12 = Young, Emerson, Stimpson\n| length12 = 4:51\n| title13 = No Place to Go\n| writer13 = Wilson\n| length13 = 3:44\n| title14 = Relax\n| writer14 = Young\n| length14 = 3:19\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1978 albums]]\n[[Category:Sad Caf\u00e9 (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Punter]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:1978 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:A&M Records compilation albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1978 album by Sad Caf\u00e9}}\n{{use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Misplaced Ideals\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Sad Caf\u00e9]]\n| cover        = Sad Caf\u00e9 Misplaced Ideals UK original.jpg\n| caption      = Original vinyl cover\n| released     = April 1978\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{hlist|[[Sawmills Studios]], Cornwall|[[Air Studios]], London}}\n| genre        = [[Pop rock]]\n| length       = 42:06\n| label        = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer     = [[John Punter]]\n| prev_title   = [[Fanx Ta-ra]]\n| prev_year    = 1977\n| next_title   = [[Misplaced Ideals#North American album|Misplaced Ideals]]\n| next_year    = 1978\n| misc         = {{Extra album cover\n | type    = album \n | header  = Alternative cover\n | cover   = Sad Caf\u00e9 Misplaced Ideals UK reissue.jpg\n | caption = Reissue vinyl cover\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Misplaced Ideals''''' is the second studio album by English rock band [[Sad Caf\u00e9]], released in April 1978<ref>{{Cite magazine|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|first=|date=22 April 1978|editor-last=|editor-first=|title=Record Mirror|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Record-Mirror/70s/78/1978-04-22.pdf|magazine=|publisher=|volume=|issue=|page=5|pages=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> by [[RCA Records]]. Despite no singles being released from the album and its lack of commercial success, it peaked at number 50 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldofgenesis.com/Biography-PaulYoung.htm|title=World of Genesis - Paul Young - A Brief History 1947-2000|website=www.worldofgenesis.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/misplaced-ideals/|title=misplaced ideals {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The album wasn't released in US or Canada, where instead it was decided that a compilation album, also titled ''[[Misplaced Ideals#North American album|Misplaced Ideals]]'', of the band's first two albums be released. \n\nThe album cover also fell under some scrutiny and RCA decided to take action and substitute it for a picture of family of sunbathers walking on a beach when it was reissued in Europe. The North American album also has a different cover<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Track Listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Restless\n| writer5 = Wilson\n| length1 = 4:38\n| title2 = Here Come the Clowns\n| writer2 = Young\n| length2 = 4:00\n| title3 = Run Home Girl\n| writer3 = Young, Wilson\n| length3 = 6:04\n| title4 = Let Love Speak for Itself\n| writer4 = Young, Stimpson, Wilson\n| length4 = 6:08\n| title5 = No Place to Go\n| writer1 = John Stimpson, [[Paul Young (singer, born 1947)|Paul Young]], Ian Wilson, Ashley Mulford\n| title6 = Mario\n| length5 = 4:51\n| writer6 = Young, [[Vic Emerson]], Stimpson\n| length6 = 3:45\n| title7 = Relax\n| writer7 = Young\n| length7 = 3:17\n| title8 = Feel Like Dying\n| writer8 = Young\n| length8 = 4:09\n| title9 = On With the Show\n| writer9 = Young, Wilson, Emerson, Mulford, Stimpson\n| length9 = 5:14\n| total_length = 42:06\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n'''Sad Caf\u00e9'''\n\n* [[Paul Young (singer, born 1947)|Paul Young]] \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n* Ashley Mulford \u2013 [[lead guitar]]\n* [[Vic Emerson]] \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n* John Stimpson \u2013 [[bass guitar]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n* Ian Wilson \u2013 [[electric guitar]], [[acoustic guitar]], backing vocals, percussion\n* Tony Cresswell \u2013 [[Drum|drums]]\n\n'''Additional personnel'''\n\n* Lenny Sachs \u2013 [[saxophone]]\n* [[John Punter]] \u2013 additional percussion\n* [[Doreen Chanter]], [[Irene Chanter]], Liza Strike \u2013 additional vocals on \"Feel Like Dying\"\n* Nigel Walker, Jon Walls \u2013 assistant engineers\n* Vic Emerson \u2013 strings arrangement and synthesisation\n* Iain Scott \u2013 photography of live band\n* [[Hipgnosis]] \u2013 sleeve design and photography\n\n== North American album ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Misplaced Ideals\n| type         = compilation\n| artist       = [[Sad Caf\u00e9]]\n| cover        = Sad Caf\u00e9 Misplaced Ideals US.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = November 1978\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Pop rock]]\n| length       = 44:20\n| label        = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| producer     = [[John Punter]]\n| next_title   = Fa\u00e7ades\n| next_year    = 1979\n}}\n\n{{album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/misplaced-ideals-mw0000793579|title=''Misplaced Ideals'' \u2013 Sad Caf\u00e9 <nowiki>| Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |</nowiki> AllMusic |last=Boldman|first=Gina|website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[Robert Christgau]]\n| rev3score = C-<ref>{{cite web|last1=Christgau|first1=Robert|title=Sad Caf\u00e9|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Sad+Cafe|website=robertchristgau.com|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThis album was only released in the US and Canada and is a compilation of songs from Sad Caf\u00e9's first two albums, ''[[Fanx Ta-ra]]'' and ''Misplaced Ideals'', neither of which were released there.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was released in November 1978 by [[A&M Records]]. \"Run Home Girl\" and \"Feel Like Dying\" were released as singles, with the former reaching number 71 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in 1979.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/sad-cafe|title=Sad Caf\u00e9|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The album also charted at number 94 on the [[Billboard 200|'